summary:
The diagnosis of severe preeclampsia requires either proteinuria exceeding 300 mg per 24 hours or a urine protein-to-creatinine ratio greater than or equal to 0.3 as defined by major obstetric organizations such as ACOG and NICE.

\boxed{B}

The summary focuses only on clinically significant information about proteinuria levels required for diagnosing severe preeclampsia without including irrelevant details like document count or tool usage steps. It correctly identifies both quantitative measures—specifically >300 mg/24hr and P/Cr ≥0.3—as essential diagnostic criteria according to established medical standards.

